<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Berlese characterized the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" genus="Mesoplophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesoplophora</taxonomicName>
as similar to &quot; 
<taxonomicName authority="Michael, 1898" authorityName="Michael" authorityYear="1898" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Hoploderma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hoploderma</taxonomicName>
&quot;, but with genital and anal openings remote from each other. Under four names he described two species of the genus; the type is 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" genus="Mesoplophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="michaeliana">Mesoplophora michaeliana</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
In 1920 Berlese described 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1904" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1904" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Phtiracarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Phtiracarulus">Phtiracarulus</taxonomicName>
, a supposed subgenus of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Phthiracarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phthiracarus</taxonomicName>
, but a study of the type-species and single representative (
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Phthiracarus" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perexiguus" subGenus="Phtiracarulus">P. perexiguus</taxonomicName>
) demonstrates that this is a juvenile 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" genus="Mesoplophora" genus.bestMatchDistance="35" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="michaeliana">M. michaeliana</taxonomicName>
; further commentary is given below 2).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
2) Willmann (1930, p. 245, figs. 8, 9) described a ptychoid mite from Guatemala, which he classified in 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phtiracarulus</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostralis">P. rostralis</taxonomicName>
); he considered the differences with 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Phthiracarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phthiracarus</taxonomicName>
sufficient to raise the subgenus to generic rank. Jacot (1938a, p. 112, pl. 9 figs. 1-5) described a closely related species (
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.bestMatchDistance="852" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevis">P. laevis</taxonomicName>
) from the U.S.A. It is difficult to separate 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="2" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevis">laevis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostralis">rostralis</taxonomicName>
, because the differential characters mentioned by Jacot (number and length of the notogastral hairs) are not evident; it is, indeed, not impossible that in the mountains of Guatamala (the type-material of 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostralis">rostralis</taxonomicName>
was collected at an altitude of 2500 feet) the same species occurs as in N. America.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Apparently, Willman still considered 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostralis">P. rostralis</taxonomicName>
a representative of the family 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phthiracaridae</taxonomicName>
. Jacot regarded the two species (
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="2" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevis">laevis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostralis">rostralis</taxonomicName>
) as highly developed 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Protoplophoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Protoplophoridae</taxonomicName>
(tribe 
<taxonomicName pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="tribe" tribe="Phtiracarulini">Phtiracarulini</taxonomicName>
Jacot, 1938a). Up to the present, nobody observed, however, the relationship with the 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mesoplophoridae</taxonomicName>
; in fact, 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostralis">rostralis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="2" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevis">laevis</taxonomicName>
remind of the scleritized nymphs of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" genus="Mesoplophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesoplophora</taxonomicName>
, although they are certainly adults. Apart from females with eggs, Jacot also described remarkable, scleritized nymphs. A reinvestigation of the large material collected by Jacot will certainly enlarge our knowledge of the systematic position of the 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mesoplophoridae</taxonomicName>
. I remark that in 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phtiracarulus</taxonomicName>
(sensu Willmann and Jacot) genital and anal plates are separated by a plate that possibly must be considered a fusion of adanals and prae-anal.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Because 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phtiracarulus Berlese</taxonomicName>
is a synonym of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" genus="Mesoplophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesoplophora</taxonomicName>
, a new genus must be created for 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phtiracarulus</taxonomicName>
sensu Willmann and Jacot. I name this genus 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" genus="Archoplophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Archoplophora</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="genus">nov. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but for the moment I refer to the diagnosis given by Jacot (1938a, p. 112, pl. 9 figs. 1-5). I designate 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1921" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1921" class="Arachnida" family="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phtiracarulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Arachnida (awaiting allocation)" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevis">Phtiracarulus laevis Jacot</taxonomicName>
(1938a) as type of the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Mesoplophoridae" genus="Archoplophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Archoplophora</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
